Here's what I've found: The deadlock is caused by holding a `std::sync::Mutex` guard across an `.await` point. In `upload_file`, the code does `store.lock().unwrap()` and then calls `store.save(&hash, &body).await` while still holding the lock. 

With `std::sync::Mutex`, the lock is tied to the OS thread. But async runtimes like tokio can suspend the task at the `.await` and resume it on a different thread. If all worker threads end up waiting to acquire the mutex while the task holding it is suspended with no thread to resume on, you get a deadlock. This becomes visible at ~100 requests because that's when the thread pool saturates.

The fix is to use `tokio::sync::Mutex` (which is async-aware) or restructure to not hold the lock across `.await`. I'll restructure, which is the more efficient approach — holding a mutex across I/O is slow regardless.

