To summarize what I'm seeing: The nginx upstream block lists three backends on ports 3000, 3001, and 3002. But `ss` shows only ports 3000 and 3001 are listening — port 3002 has no process. When nginx round-robins to 3002, it gets `Connection refused` (error 111), which it returns to the client as a 502. About 1 in 3 requests would fail.

The immediate fix is to either start the third Node instance on port 3002 or remove it from the upstream block. I'll also add `max_fails` and `fail_timeout` so nginx automatically stops routing to a dead backend instead of serving 502s.

